Hey there! First of all, thanks for the talk at FB London today. Re: the question I asked about iterables, this is the kind of examples I was thinking of that I said I see a lot (untested, but you get the idea):

```python
def always_the_same(elements):
    '''Check whether every element in an iterable is equal'''
    if not elements:
        return True
    return all(elements[0] is x for x in elements)
```

In this case, we might have an unindexable type of iterable, so even though this usually works since most people will probably just pass in a list or tuple, it breaks on generators/other non-indexable things. People might still use Hypothesis just to generate a bunch of lists or tuples in this case thinking it is good enough, but if there was a distinct "iterable" class, it could be used except in cases where an indexable iterable was *really* necessary.

```python
def print_twice(elements):
    for item in elements:
        yield item
    for item in elements:
        yield item
```

This is a particularly dumb example, but you get the idea. Mostly I see this when multiple for loops may be used to iterate over something, and the person writing the function didn't consider generator exhaustion.

I think it's worth having an "iterable" strategy just because I think that it's quite possible that when many people say some function "takes an iterable", they may not have considered the consequences of iterables that don't allow indexing, or can become exhausted (just like every Python programmer, I make this assumption without realising it every now and then).

I may take a look at how the scenario generator works and put some code to go with this request, assuming, of course, that my proposal makes sense to you and you think it adds value.

Thanks!

